data.content:
MSTest has a dedicated `CollectionAssert` class plus better assertion alternatives. Here's your test improved:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Use Assert.AreEqual for exact counts — clearer failure messages
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // Use CollectionAssert for collection-specific checks
    CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users);

    // Assert.IsTrue is fine for predicate checks over elements
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), "Expected all users to be active");

    // Use Assert.IsNotNull instead of Assert.IsTrue(x != null)
    var admin = users.SingleOrDefault(u => u.Role == "Admin");
    Assert.IsNotNull(admin, "Expected an Admin user");
}
```

**Key improvements:**

| Instead of | Use | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count > 0)` | `Assert.AreEqual(3, count)` | Exact check; failure message shows expected vs actual |
| `Assert.IsTrue(obj != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(obj)` | Clearer intent and failure output |
| `Single()` (throws) | `SingleOrDefault()` + `IsNotNull` | Controlled failure instead of unhandled exception |

**Other useful `CollectionAssert` methods:**

- `CollectionAssert.Contains(collection, element)`
- `CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expected, actual)` — same order
- `CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expected, actual)` — any order
- `CollectionAssert.IsSubsetOf(subset, superset)`
- `CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreUnique(collection)`

The general rule: prefer the most specific assertion available — you get much better failure messages than a bare `Assert.IsTrue`.
